## ⌥R.* Regex Mode — Detailed Guide

Regular Expressions let a single pattern match many channel names or keywords at once.

### Format Rules

- **Enter the pattern directly** — no leading `/` or trailing `/i` needed
- **Case-insensitive by default** (equivalent to the `/i` flag always being on)
- Flag syntax is not supported — writing `memes/i` treats `/i` as part of the pattern

### Channel Name Regex (Blocklist / Whitelist)

Check **⌥R.* Regex mode** when adding a channel, then enter your pattern:

| Pattern | Effect |
|---------|--------|
| `memes` | Channel name contains `memes` **anywhere** (case-insensitive) |
| `^memes` | Channel name **starts with** `memes` |
| `memes$` | Channel name **ends with** `memes` |
| `\bmemes\b` | `memes` is a **standalone word** in the channel name |
| `(shorts\|clips)` | Matches channel names containing `shorts` or `clips` |
| `^NASA$` | Exact full match for `NASA` (case-insensitive) |

> **Note:** Channel Regex matches the **channel name only**, not the @handle / channel ID. To filter by handle, use the exact @handle with Regex mode off.

### ✅ When to use Regex — and when to just type the name

**Directly entering a channel name** is the most common approach. Regex is only worth using when channel names share a clear, predictable pattern.

**Good use cases for Regex:**

| Scenario | Pattern |
|----------|---------|
| Block all channels ending with "Gaming" | `Gaming$` |
| Block channels containing "News" or "Politics" | `(News\|Politics)` |
| Block reaction / commentary channels | `(react\|reaction\|commentary)` |

**When to skip Regex and just type names directly:**

If you want to block channels with completely unrelated names, a single Regex cannot cover all of them accurately. Simply add each channel name individually without enabling Regex mode.

> **Rule of thumb:** If you find yourself writing `(A|B|C)` to list completely unrelated names, add them as separate exact-match entries instead.

### Common Pitfalls

- Special characters (`. * + ? ( ) [ ] { } ^ $ | \`) have special meanings in Regex. To match them literally, prefix with a backslash — e.g. `\[SPONSORED\]`
- An invalid pattern (mismatched parentheses, etc.) silently fails to match anything — no error is shown
- Test your patterns at [regex101.com](https://regex101.com) before adding them

